    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay thanks. so if the escrow agent is a neutral third party, what happens if there is a dispute? like if the seller doesn't fix something they promised to fix before closing, can the escrow agent just hold onto the money indefinitely?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In the event of a dispute, such as the seller failing to make promised repairs before closing, the escrow agent's role becomes crucial. The escrow agent acts as a mediator and holds the funds in the escrow account until the dispute is resolved. If the issue is not resolved by the agreed-upon closing date, the funds may not be released to the seller, and the buyer may have grounds to delay closing or seek legal remedies.\n\nThe escrow agent will typically follow the instructions outlined in the purchase agreement and any relevant laws or regulations. If the seller does not fulfill their obligations, the buyer may have the right to withhold payment or seek compensation for the unresolved issues. It's important to note that the specific actions taken by the escrow agent will depend on the terms of the purchase agreement and the nature of the dispute.\n\nIn some cases, the buyer may need to involve their attorney or real estate agent to help resolve the issue and ensure that their rights are protected. It's always a good idea to have a clear understanding of the terms of the purchase agreement and to communicate openly with the seller and the escrow agent throughout the process. I hope this helps clarify what happens in the event of a dispute involving an escrow account.",
      "source": "target",
